{
  "properties": {
    "rigidity": "+R",
    "identity": "-I",
    "own_identity": "-O",
    "unity": "-U",
    "dependence": "-D"
  },
  "classification": "Quality",
  "reasoning": "The term 'Entity' is the most general property in the ontology. It is Rigid (+R) because if something is an entity, it is necessarily an entity in all possible worlds. However, it does not carry (-I) or supply (-O) a specific identity condition, as the criteria for identifying one entity from another depend on more specific types (e.g., Person vs. Organization). It does not guarantee Unity (-U) because an entity can be a single object or an aggregate, and it is independent (-D) as it represents the root of existence."
}

{
  "properties": {
    "rigidity": "+R",
    "identity": "+I",
    "own_identity": "+O",
    "unity": "-U",
    "dependence": "-D"
  },
  "classification": "Natural Kind",
  "reasoning": "Location is typically defined as a rigid property (+R) because a spatial or conceptual coordinate cannot cease to be a location without losing its nature. It supplies its own identity conditions (+I, +O) based on spatial reference systems or unique identifiers. It is non-unifying (-U) because a location (like a region) can be composed of smaller locations without necessarily forming a single organic whole. It is independent (-D) as it represents a space or position that does not require the presence of a specific physical entity to exist."
}

{
  "properties": {
    "rigidity": "+R",
    "identity": "+I",
    "own_identity": "+O",
    "unity": "~U",
    "dependence": "-D"
  },
  "classification": "Natural Kind",
  "reasoning": "According to Guarino and Welty (2000), AmountOfMatter is Rigid (+R) because if something is an amount of matter, it cannot cease to be so without ceasing to exist. It is Anti-Unified (~U) because it is divisible into parts that are also the same matter, lacking a whole-part structure with a boundary. It does not supply its own Identity Condition (-O) nor carry one (-I) because we cannot distinguish between 'this' amount and 'that' amount based solely on the property itself without external units of measure."
}

{
  "properties": {
    "rigidity": "-R",
    "identity": "-I",
    "own_identity": "-O",
    "unity": "-U",
    "dependence": "-D"
  },
  "classification": "Mixin",
  "reasoning": "Color properties like 'Red' are anti-rigid (~R) because an object can change color without losing its identity (it is not essential). It does not provide identity conditions (-I) as it cannot distinguish individual instances of red objects by itself, nor does it define a whole (+U) or necessarily depend on a specific external entity (+D) beyond its substrate."
}

{
  "properties": {
    "rigidity": "~R",
    "identity": "-I",
    "own_identity": "-O",
    "unity": "-U",
    "dependence": "+D"
  },
  "classification": "Phase Mixin",
  "reasoning": "Agent is anti-rigid (~R) because an entity can become an agent or cease to be one without losing its identity (e.g., a Person becomes an Agent when performing an action). It carries identity (+I) inherited from its backbone sortal, but does not supply its own (+O). It is externally dependent (+D) on an action or goal being pursued."
}

{
  "properties": {
    "rigidity": "+R",
    "identity": "+I",
    "own_identity": "+O",
    "unity": "-U",
    "dependence": "-D"
  },
  "classification": "Natural Kind",
  "reasoning": "A Group is rigid because its members cannot cease to be a group and remain the same type of entity. It supplies its own identity conditions (+O) based on membership criteria. It is characterized by Anti-Unity (~U) because it is an aggregate or collection of distinct individuals rather than a single topological whole, and it is dependent (+D) because the existence of a group relies on the existence of its constituent members."
}

{
  "properties": {
    "rigidity": "+R",
