  },
  "classification": "Natural Kind",
  "reasoning": "Animal is a rigid property because an instance cannot cease to be an animal without ceasing to exist. It supplies its own identity conditions (IC) for its instances and defines a common unity criterion (biological wholeness)."
}

{
  "properties": {
    "rigidity": "+R",
    "identity": "+I",
    "own_identity": "+O",
    "unity": "+U",
    "dependence": "-D"
  },
  "classification": "Natural Kind",
  "reasoning": "SocialEntity is Rigid (+R) because if an entity is social, it is essentially so within the context of its defined existence. It does not supply its own Identity Condition (-O) or carry one (-I) because it is a high-level generalization that includes wildly different individuals (e.g., organizations and legal departments) that do not share a common identity criterion. It is Non-Unifying (-U) as it does not dictate a specific whole-part relationship, and it is Dependent (+D) because a SocialEntity necessarily depends on the existence of agents or a social community to be constituted."
}

{
  "properties": {
    "rigidity": "+R",
    "identity": "+I",
    "own_identity": "+O",
    "unity": "+U",
    "dependence": "-D"
  },
  "classification": "Natural Kind",
  "reasoning": "Apple is a rigid property because an instance of an apple cannot cease to be an apple without losing its identity (it doesn't change into another kind of thing). It provides its own identity conditions for distinguishing one apple from another and defines a whole organism/fruit (Unity). It is not inherently dependent on another entity for its basic existence."
}

{
